Vice President Mike Pence delivered a speech at the Munich Security Conference, reaffirming the United States' commitment to NATO and its allies. He emphasized the importance of peace and prosperity in Europe and the North Atlantic, stating that the US will be unwavering in its support for the transatlantic alliance. Pence also called on NATO members to fulfill their commitment to contribute 2% of their GDP to defense spending. He highlighted the threats posed by rogue nations developing nuclear weapons, radical Islamic terrorism, and the destabilization caused by the rise of extremist groups. Pence assured that the US, under President Trump's leadership, will strengthen its military and work with allies to confront these challenges. He also emphasized the importance of cooperation in counter-terrorism efforts and increasing cyber capabilities. Pence concluded by stating that the US and Europe share a past and a future, and that the US will always be Europe's greatest ally.